Apparently, the names in colors are not accidental and have an undisclosed symbolic meaning [9]. European minds have been wrestling with the question of the origins of the Nile since the time of Herodotus, who in his History refuted the opinion that the Nile flood comes from melting snow in its upper reaches. According to the map of Herodotus, the Nile merges with the Niger. In addition, the “father of history” cites the news of the Sais priest that the waters of the Nile gush from the land between Siena (now Aswan) and Elephantine, with half of them flowing south, and the other half - to the north. None of the famous travelers of antiquity climbed the Nile higher than Sedda.